hey reveal the inner conflicts of ordinary Germans who became reluctant accomplices in Hitler's merciless war of annihilation, yet sometimes managed to discover a shared humanity with its suffering victims, a bond that could transcend race, nationalism, and the enmity of war. Reluctant Accomplice is also the powerful story of the son, who for decades refused to come to grips with these letters because he abhorred his father's nationalist politics. Only now, late in his life, is he able to cope with their contents--and he is by no means alone. This book provides rare insight into the so-called children of the war, an entire generation of postwar Germans who grew up resenting their past, but who today must finally face the painful legacy of their parents' complicity in National Socialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aIntellectualszGermanyvCorrespondence. 0aSoldierszGermanyvCorrespondence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, German. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocities. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCampaignszEastern Front. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMoral and ethical aspects. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aAdolf Hitler.  aDulag.  aGermans.  aJews.  aKonrad Jarausch.  aNational Socialism.  aNazi Germany.  aNazis.  aNazism.  aPoland.  aPoles.  aProtestant Church.  aProtestant pedagogy.  aThird Reich.  aUSSR.  aWorld War II.  aarmy training.  achildren.  acomplicity.  aeducation.  agenocide.  ahumanism.  ahumanity.  aimperialism.  aletters.  anationalism.  anew recruits.  aprisoner of war.  atransnational humanity.1 aJarausch, Konrad H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKohn, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohn, Richard.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G